post_text: You may have seen a post on Facebook earlier tonight with a threat to Hamilton High. School administration, staff and faculty have been notified. Hamilton County Sheriff's Office and FDLE are investigating. All indications are that this is coming out of Tennessee and was a threat to Hamilton High in Memphis and is NOT a credible threat to Hamilton County High School, Jasper, FL. However, all necessary precautions for student safety are being followed. The HCSO will have additional presence on campus tomorrow. As always student safety is paramount and our number one priority. Please share this information.

post_text:
The Hamilton County School District in conjunction with Hamilton County Emergency Management are working with the National Weather Service out of Jacksonville, for the most up to date predictions and safety recommendations for Tropical Depression #9 in Hamilton County.

If weather becomes a safety issue for students, staff, transportation, or school operation, the District will communicate directly to the community via phone callouts, school callouts, as well as web page and social media updates.

The safety and security of our students/staff is our first concern daily and we will not put either in harm’s way.

More updates to follow over the next 24 hours. If a decision needs to be made altering school operations based on recommendations from Emergency Management, expect a communication Wednesday evening between 8-9 pm.

post_text:
Central Hamilton Elementary is a bronze-award recipient for the HealthierUS School Challenge: Smarter Lunchrooms program. This national program is a voluntary certification initiative, recognizing schools that create healthier school environments by promoting good nutrition and physical activity.

Since the program's launch, more than seven thousand schools throughout the country have achieved certification. As a certified school, Central Hamilton will receive $500 from the USDA. Congratulations to everyone involved on this accomplishment!

post_text:
Steve Carpenter and Glenn Davis from the Suwannee Forestry Center recently presented the Superintendent with a check for $34,640.27. The payment reflects the distribution of the Twin Rivers State Forest receipts for fiscal year 2013-14, in accordance with Section 589, Florida Statutes.

The Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services manages 36 state forests, and last year, the Department collected over $7 million from the operation of those forests, through the collection of recreation fees and the sale of timber.

Ten counties that are home to the state's incoming-producing forests benefit from the operation of the forests. These counties are deemed fiscally constrained and receive 15% of the gross receipts, in proportion to the acreage located in each county. Based on 2013-14 gross receipts, the Department will distribute more than $370,000 to the various counties.

post_text:
Press Release - Recognition of First Responders

On Monday, Governor Rick Scott proclaimed the first week of January as Florida First Responders Appreciation Week. In recognition of Hamilton County’s law enforcement officers, EMTs, and firefighters, our school district will provide lunch to them on Friday, January 9.

First responders may visit any of our schools and enjoy lunch, courtesy of the school system. This is but a small token of appreciation for the fine work they do in keeping our county safe. We encourage first responders to visit the school of their choice tomorrow between 11:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. and inform the main office of their arrival.

To the men and women who risk their lives daily to ensure the safety of our students and citizens, thank you for your service!

First responders may visit any of our schools and enjoy lunch, courtesy of the school system. This is but a small token of appreciation for the fine work they do in keeping our county safe. We encourage first responders to visit the school of their choice tomorrow between 11:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. and inform the main office of their arrival.

To the men and women who risk their lives daily to ensure the safety of our students and citizens, thank you for your service!

post_text: Blair Armstrong is returning to Florida, after coaching 13 years in Georgia, as the new Hamilton County Head Football coach and math instructor. Coach Armstrong brings back a state championship ring from Georgia to add to the one he won in Florida at Jefferson County High. He plans to be here soon to build a coaching staff and get the players ready for spring practice. His goal is to develop discipline, character, and leadership while making the game fun.

He has been contracted through June 30, 2013 and he will be in charge of staff, discipline, and students. post_text: We are proud to recognize high school juniors Tiffany Walton and Ismelda Alvarez. Tiffany and Ismelda recently participated in the Annual Youth Tour in Tallahassee. During this event, participants were tested, and the two students with the highest test scores received all-expenses-paid trips to Washington, D.C. We are excited to announce that Ismelda was one of the top scorers and she will travel to Washington, D.C. in June. Congratulations, Tiffany and Ismelda, and thank you for representing our school district so well!

post_text: At the recent regional science fair, HCHS student Tyler Warfel received second place in the senior environmental division. He will represent the school at the state science fair in Lakeland next month. Tyler was also chosen for the GENIUS Olympiad, an international high school project competition about environmental issues. The competition is co-organized by the State University of New York at Oswego and the Terra Science and Education Foundation. GENIUS Olympiad 2013 will be held in New York in June. Congratulations, Tyler, and best of luck as you represent the high school and Hamilton County!

post_text: The Hamilton County High Trojan boys’ basketball team won its second district championship in the last eight years Saturday night in Mayo. The Trojans defeated Melody Christian Academy 49-47 in a very well-played contest. Head coach Patrick Murphy would like to thank assistant coaches Mike Cohen, Steve Troy, Travis Glover and Ti'Wan Cooks for all of their help throughout the season. The season continues into the playoffs on Tuesday the 19th vs. Hilliard at home. Game will begin at 7:00.

post_text: The Hamilton County High Trojan girls’ basketball team won its second consecutive district championship Saturday night in Branford. The Lady Trojans defeated Branford High Scholl 38-37 in a very well-played contest. Head coach Greg Taylor would like to thank assistant coaches Tiffani Sheppard, Jesse Sheppard, and Geadon Smith for all of their help and support throughout the season. The girls will advance to the Regional Semi-finals on Tuesday the 12th vs. Hawthorne at home. Game will begin at 7:00.

post_text:
Florida Representative Michael Bileca (Chair), Mrs. Lee Zamora (CHE Principal), and Sam Foerster (FL DOE) after Mrs. Zamora testified in front of the Florida House Choice and Innovation Subcommittee January 15, 2013.

Central Hamilton Elementary was recognized for the following:

"Central Hamilton Elementary demonstrated the most improvement in the FCAT portion of the school grading formula (76 points) of
all 158 traditional (non-charter) combination schools between 2010-2011 and 2011-2012." and

"Central Hamilton Elementary was in the top 3% of all elementary schools in the state in terms of school grade improvement between 2010-2011 and 2011-2012."

Congratulations on a job well done!

post_text: This morning, an emergency lock-down DRILL was conducted at Hamilton County High School. In addition, the Hamilton County Sheriff’s Office completed a drug dog walk-through of the high school’s parking lots. The Hamilton County Emergency Management and Sheriff’s Department teams did an amazing job assisting us in our continued safety efforts. The administration, staff, and students at Hamilton County High reacted with professionalism and in accordance with our district’s emergency action plan. Everyone involved is to be commended.

post_text:
The Florida Department of Education released the 2012 high school grades and Hamilton County High School was awarded the letter grade of D. This is a decrease from the 2011 school grade of C. The grading criteria was changed for the 2012 cycle; we are reviewing how those changes affected our grade so we can make improvements for the 2013 cycle. You may review the complete FLDOE report at http://schoolgrades.fldoe.org.

A detailed briefing of the HCHS scores will be provided at the January 28, 2013 Board Workshop beginning at 4 pm.
